{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:56:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:56:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18636"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18636"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.2,0.51,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80228"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11368"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65512"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80228"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman undergoes computed tomography angiography of the chest as part of a research study examining bronchial artery anatomy. The radiologist is particularly interested in identifying the origins of these vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical origin of the bronchial arteries?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All bronchial arteries arise from the brachiocephalic trunk","Right and left bronchial arteries arise from the internal thoracic arteries","Right bronchial artery from third posterior intercostal artery, two left bronchial arteries from descending thoracic aorta","Three bronchial arteries arise directly from the aortic arch","Single common bronchial trunk arises from the ascending aorta"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright bronchial artery from third posterior intercostal artery, two left bronchial arteries from descending thoracic aorta\u003C/strong\u003E represents the typical anatomical arrangement. This provides systemic arterial blood to nourish the bronchi and pulmonary tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll bronchial arteries arise from the brachiocephalic trunk\u003C/strong\u003E - The brachiocephalic trunk divides into the right subclavian and right common carotid arteries; it does not supply bronchial arteries\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight and left bronchial arteries arise from the internal thoracic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The internal thoracic arteries supply the anterior chest wall, not the bronchi\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree bronchial arteries arise directly from the aortic arch\u003C/strong\u003E - The bronchial arteries originate below the level of the aortic arch\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle common bronchial trunk arises from the ascending aorta\u003C/strong\u003E - The ascending aorta does not give rise to any branches except the coronary arteries\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding bronchial artery anatomy is clinically important in conditions such as hemoptysis, where these vessels may require embolisation, and in lung transplantation, where bronchial artery reconstruction may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The bronchial arteries provide systemic oxygenated blood to the airways and pulmonary tissue.","The right bronchial artery typically originates from the third posterior intercostal artery.","Two left bronchial arteries usually arise directly from the descending thoracic aorta."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18636"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65512"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-18T14:01:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-18T14:03:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11368"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80228"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag